
[1]plausible

   PLAUS'IBLE, a. s as z. [L. plausibilis, from plaudo, to clap hands in
   token of approbation; laus, laudo; Eng. loud.]

   1. That may be applauded; that may gain favor or approbation; hence,
   superficially pleasing; apparently right; specious; popular; as a
   plausible argument; a plausible pretext; a plausible doctrine.

   2. Using specious arguments or discourse; as a plausible man.
